<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    Cleartext is permitted by default.

    A previous iteration of this file tried to deny cleartext globally and
    re-allow it for RFC-1918 / Tailscale IP ranges.  That approach is broken:
    Android's <domain> matcher is suffix-based hostname matching, NOT
    CIDR/subnet matching, so an entry like "192.168.0.0" only matches the
    literal hostname "192.168.0.0" — it does not match 192.168.1.5.  In
    practice that meant cleartext was denied for every real LAN host (Ollama,
    OpenClaw, Home Assistant) the user might configure.

    Re-permitting cleartext globally is safe in this app's threat model
    because:
      • Every public LLM provider URL hardcoded in /llm/providers/ is HTTPS.
        OkHttp picks the scheme from the URL, so this config has no effect on
        those calls.
      • The only cleartext flows are user-configured self-hosted services on
        their own LAN / VPN, where the user has explicitly opted in by
        entering an http:// URL in Settings.
      • User-installed CAs are trusted so users running their own HTTPS with
        a private CA can still benefit from TLS without bundling certs.

    Future work: when Android exposes proper IP-range matching in NSC, switch
    back to deny-by-default with explicit RFC-1918 / 100.64/10 ranges allowed.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true">
        <trust-anchors>
            <certificates src="system" />
            <certificates src="user" />
        </trust-anchors>
    </base-config>
</network-security-config>
